Penalized Regression Approaches for Time Series Representation

1. Reading the Data and Visualization

In brief, this homework explains how we can construct some penalized regression approaches for time series. First of all, we have constrcuted 1D Fused Lasso representation with k = 10 and found the best lambda values for each time series. Then, we have constructed regression tree with different maxdepth values. Then, we have calculated the MSE values between for each time series on the dataset for 1D Fused Lasso model with best lambda value and the regression tree model with best maxdepth value. Moreover, we have created 1-nearest-neighborhood (1-NN) model. Also, we have checked the Euclidian distances between the excluded points for each model; 1D Fused Lasso, regression tree, and 1-NN. Finally, we have predicted the excluded points’ classes and checked whether we made predictions correct or not, and calculated accuracy values fore ach class

Question - 1

Firstly, we are going to exclude each 1 observation from 10 observations, i.e. k = 10, for each time series to test 1D Fused Lasso model on the excluded data. Yet, exclusion didn’t mean that we have excluded the point permanently, we have just used these excluded points on our representations to check our representations and their results. Then, we needed to find the optimal lambda values for each time series to complete 1D Fused Lasso model. Yet, as you can see from the plots, the minimum lambda values didn’t give the best result since it causes overly fitted values for the predicted values; therefore, we had to use 1-standard-error rule and use the lambda values giving 1-standard-error values.
